Theorem: Equality of Elements in Range of Mapping

Proof:


=== Necessary Condition ===
Let:
:$\exists y \in \Rng f: \tuple {x_1, y} \in f \land \tuple {x_2, y} \in f$
Then:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | o =
      | r = \tuple {x_1, y} \in f \land \tuple {x_2, y} \in f
      | c =
}}
{{eqn | o = \leadsto
      | r = \map f {x_1} = y \land \map f {x_2} = y
      | c = {{Defof|Mapping}}
}}
{{eqn | o = \leadsto
      | r = \map f {x_1} = \map f {x_2}
      | c = [[Equality is Equivalence Relation]]
}}
{{end-eqn}}
{{qed|lemma}}
=== Sufficient Condition ===
Let:
:$\map f {x_1} = \map f {x_2}$
Then:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | o =
      | r = \forall y \in \Rng f: \map f {x_1} = y = \map f {x_2}
      | c =
}}
{{eqn | o = \leadsto
      | r = \exists y \in \Rng f: \tuple {x_1, y} \in f \land \tuple {x_2, y} \in f
      | c = {{Defof|Mapping}}
}}
{{end-eqn}}
{{qed|lemma}}
The result follows from the definition of [[Definition:Logical Equivalence|logical equivalence]].
{{qed}}
