Theorem: Set Difference with Intersection

Proof:

Consider $R, S, T \subseteq \mathbb U$, where $\mathbb U$ is considered as the [[Definition:Universe (Set Theory)|universe]].
Then:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l = \left({R \setminus S}\right) \cap T
      | r = \left({R \cap \complement \left({S}\right)}\right) \cap T
      | c = [[Set Difference as Intersection with Complement]]
}}
{{eqn | r = \left({R \cap T}\right) \cap \complement \left({S}\right)
      | c = [[Intersection is Commutative]] and [[Intersection is Associative]]
}}
{{eqn | r = \left({R \cap T}\right) \setminus S
      | c = [[Set Difference as Intersection with Complement]]
}}
{{end-eqn}}
{{qed}}

