Theorem: Invertible Element of Associative Structure is Cancellable

Proof:


Let $a \in S$ be [[Definition:Invertible Element|invertible]].
Suppose $a \circ x = a \circ y$.
Then:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l = x
      | r = x \circ e_S
      | c = Behaviour of [[Definition:Identity Element|Identity]]
}}
{{eqn | r = x \circ (a^{-1} \circ a)
      | c = Behaviour of [[Definition:Inverse Element|Inverse]]
}}
{{eqn | r = (x \circ a^{-1}) \circ a
      | c = [[Definition:Associative Operation|Associativity]] of $\circ$
}}
{{eqn | r = (y \circ a^{-1}) \circ a
      | c = [[Definition:By Hypothesis|By Hypothesis]]
}}
{{eqn | r = y \circ (a^{-1} \circ a)
      | c = [[Definition:Associative Operation|Associativity]] of $\circ$
}}
{{eqn | r = y \circ e_S
      | c = Behaviour of [[Definition:Inverse Element|Inverse]]
}}
{{eqn | r = y
      | c = Behaviour of [[Definition:Identity Element|Identity]]
}}
{{end-eqn}}
A similar argument shows that $x \circ a = y \circ a \implies x = y$.
{{Qed}}


