Theorem: Intersection of Subsemigroups

Proof:

Let $T = T_1 \cap T_2$ where $T_1, T_2$ are [[Definition:Subsemigroup|subsemigroups]] of $\left({S, \circ}\right)$. Then:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | o =
      | r = a, b \in T
}}
{{eqn | o = \implies
      | r = a, b \in T_1 \land a, b \in T_2
      | c = {{Defof|Set Intersection}}
}}
{{eqn | o = \implies
      | r = a \circ b \in T_1 \land a \circ b \in T_2
      | c = [[Definition:Subsemigroup|Subsemigroups are closed]]
}}
{{eqn | o = \implies
      | r = a \circ b \in T
      | c = {{Defof|Set Intersection}}
}}
{{end-eqn}}
Thus $\left({T, \circ}\right)$ is [[Definition:Closed Algebraic Structure|closed]], and is therefore a semigroup from the [[Subsemigroup Closure Test]].
{{Qed}}
The other results follow from this and [[Intersection is Subset]].
[[Category:Set Intersection]]
