Theorem: Equivalence of Definitions of Reflexive Relation

Proof:


=== [[Definition:Reflexive Relation/Definition 1|Definition 1]] implies [[Definition:Reflexive Relation/Definition 2|Definition 2]] ===  
Let $\RR$ be a [[Definition:Relation|relation]].  
We use a [[Proof by Contraposition]] by showing that:  
:$\Delta_S \not \subseteq \RR \implies \forall x \in S: \tuple {x, x} \notin \RR$  
Thus, suppose:  
:$\Delta_S \not \subseteq \RR$  
Then by definition of [[Definition:Diagonal Relation|Diagonal Relation]]:  
:$\exists \tuple {x, x} \in S \times S: \tuple {x, x} \notin \RR$  
Thus:  
:$\forall x \in S: \tuple {x, x} \notin \RR$  
From [[Rule of Transposition]] it follows that:  
:$\forall x \in S: \tuple {x, x} \in \RR \implies \Delta_S \subseteq \RR$  
{{qed|lemma}}  

=== [[Definition:Reflexive Relation/Definition 2|Definition 2]] implies [[Definition:Reflexive Relation/Definition 1|Definition 1]] ===  
Let $\RR$ be a [[Definition:Relation|relation]] which fulfils the condition:  
:$\Delta_S \subseteq \RR$  
Then:  
{{begin-eqn}}  
{{eqn | l = \forall x \in S \times S: \tuple {x, x}
      | o = \in
      | r = \Delta_S
      | c = {{Defof|Diagonal Relation}}
}}  
{{eqn | ll= \leadsto
      | l = \forall x \in S \times S: \tuple {x, x}
      | o = \in
      | r = \RR
      | c = {{Defof|Subset}}
}}  
{{end-eqn}}  
Thus $\RR$ is [[Definition:Reflexive Relation/Definition 1|reflexive by Definition 1]].  
{{Qed}}


