Theorem: Max and Min are Commutative

Proof:


To simplify our notation:
: Let $\max \left({x, y}\right)$ be (temporarily) denoted $x \overline \wedge y$
: Let $\min \left({x, y}\right)$ be (temporarily) denoted $x \underline \vee y$.
There are three cases to consider:
:$(1): \quad x \le y$
:$(2): \quad y \le x$
:$(3): \quad x = y$
$(1): \quad$ Let $x \le y$.
Then:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l=x \overline \wedge y
      | r=y
      | rr==y \overline \wedge x
}}
{{eqn | l=x \underline \vee y
      | r=y
      | rr==y \underline \vee x
}}
{{end-eqn}}
$(2): \quad$ Let $y \le x$.
Then:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l=x \overline \wedge y
      | r=x
      | rr==y \overline \wedge x
}}
{{eqn | l=x \underline \vee y
      | r=y
      | rr==y \underline \vee x
}}
{{end-eqn}}
$(3): \quad$ Let $x = y$.
Then:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l=x \overline \wedge y
      | r=x = y
      | rr==y \overline \wedge x
}}
{{eqn | l=x \underline \vee y
      | r=x = y
      | rr==y \underline \vee x
}}
{{end-eqn}}
Thus $\overline \wedge$, i.e. $\max$, and $\underline \vee$, i.e. $\min$, have been shown to be [[Definition:Commutative Operation|commutative]] in all cases.
{{qed}}
