Theorem: Surjection if Composite is Surjection

Proof:

Let $g \circ f$ be [[Definition:Surjection|surjective]].
Fix $z \in S_3$. 
Now find an $x \in S_1: \map {g \circ f} x = z$.
The surjectivity of $g \circ f$ guarantees this can be done.
Now find an $y \in S_2: f \paren x = y$.
$f$ is a [[Definition:Mapping|mapping]] and therefore a [[Definition:Left-Total Relation|left-total relation]]; which guarantees this too can be done.
It follows that:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l = \map g y
      | r = \map g {\map f x}
}}
{{eqn | r = \map {g \circ f} x
      | c = {{Defof|Composition of Mappings}}
}}
{{eqn | r = z
      | c = Choice of $x$
}}
{{end-eqn}}
{{qed}}

