Theorem: Mapping is Constant iff Image is Singleton

Proof:

=== Necessary Condition ===
Let $f_c: S \to T$ be a [[Definition:Constant Mapping|constant mapping]]. Then from the definition of the [[Definition:Image of Element under Mapping|image of a element]]:
:$\forall x \in S: \map {f_c} x = c \implies \Img S = \set c$
Thus the [[Definition:Image of Mapping|image]] of $f_c: S \to T$ is a [[Definition:Singleton|singleton]].
=== Sufficient Condition ===
Let $f: S \to T$ such that its image is a singleton $\set c \subseteq T$.
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l = \forall x \in S: \map f x
      | o = \in
      | r = \Img f
      | c = {{Defof|Image of Mapping}}
}}
{{eqn | ll= \leadsto
      | l = \forall x \in S: \map f x
      | o = \in
      | r = \set c
      | c = [[Definition:By Hypothesis|By Hypothesis]]
}}
{{eqn | ll= \leadsto
      | l = \forall x \in S: \map f x
      | r = c
      | c = {{Defof|Singleton}}
}}
{{end-eqn}}
Thus $f: S \to T$ is a [[Definition:Constant Mapping|constant mapping]] (and we can write it $f_c: S \to T$).
{{qed}}

