Theorem: Composite of Surjections is Surjection

Proof:


Let $f: S_1 \to S_2$ and $g: S_2 \to S_3$ be [[Definition:Surjection|surjections]].
Then:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l = \forall z \in S_3: \exists y \in S_2: \map g y
      | r = z
      | c = {{Defof|Surjection}}
}}
{{eqn | ll= \leadsto
      | l = \exists x \in S_1: \map f x
      | r = y
      | c = {{Defof|Surjection}}
}}
{{end-eqn}}
By definition of a [[Definition:Composition of Mappings|composite mapping]]:
:$\map {g \circ f} x = \map g {\map f x} = \map g y = z$
Hence $g \circ f$ is [[Definition:Surjection|surjective]].
{{qed}}


